EPISTLE XIV.

This epistle is addressed by Horace to his steward in the coun- try, showing him the folly of preferring a life in the city to one in the country. He says this preference arises from inconstancy of mind, and a love of change. For this steward had been transfer- red, at his own eamest request, from Rome to his present situa- tion. -
